1.3.1 Discrete events
---------------------

‘when’ clauses in the .mo file are auto-extracted by ‘mod_load’ and
stored in the model struct's ‘events’ field.  ‘mod_simulate_nonlinear’
uses them by default.  Inspect what was extracted with ‘mod_print’:

events:
   when  h <= 0 and v < 0 :  [v = -e*v]

To run with the auto-extracted events, just call
‘mod_simulate_nonlinear’ without the ‘'events’ opt:

[t, x] : mod_simulate_nonlinear(m_ball, [10.0, 0.0],
                                lambda([t], []),
                                5.0,
                                ['return = 'states])$

Three modes for the ‘'events’ opt:

   • *‘'auto’* (default) -- use ‘mod_get(m, 'events)’.
   • *‘[]’* -- disable event handling (pure continuous integration, even
     if the model has ‘when’ clauses).
   • *explicit list* -- override the auto-extraction.  Each entry is
     ‘[detector, reset_eqs]’ or ‘[detector, reset_eqs, guard]’:
        • ‘detector’ -- a Maxima expression in the state symbols.  Its
          zero crossings (detected by SUNDIALS' rootfinder) trigger the
          event.
        • ‘reset_eqs’ -- list of state-reset equations applied at the
          event time.  Variables not mentioned keep their current value.
        • ‘guard’ (optional) -- a Maxima expression evaluated at event
          time; the reset is applied only if ‘guard > 0’.  Used to
          translate compound ‘when’ conditions (‘h <= 0 AND v < 0’)
          faithfully.  Defaults to ‘true’.

The integrator runs segment-by-segment between requested sample times.
When CVODE reports a zero-crossing, the loop evaluates the guard at the
event-time state -- if positive, applies the reset and restarts from a
tiny Euler half-step past the event (so CVODE doesn't immediately
re-detect the boundary).  If the guard is non-positive, the detection is
treated as spurious and integration continues without a reset.  A
watchdog (100 events per segment, 1 ms dedup window) breaks Zeno-like
loops.

See ‘examples/BouncingBall.mo’ and the ‘04_events’ notebook for a
complete worked example.


